      <p><strong>Total 5-Year Tax Savings:</strong> ~RM100,000+ (depending on your income level)</p>

      <h2>Hire Purchase vs. Operating Lease: Tax Comparison</h2>

      <h3>Hire Purchase (Ownership)</h3>

      <p><strong>Deductions:</strong>
      <br>✓ Capital allowance (depreciation)
      <br>✓ Interest payments
      <br>✓ Insurance, maintenance, repairs</p>

      <p><strong>Ownership:</strong>
      <br>✓ Asset on balance sheet
      <br>✓ Builds business net worth
      <br>✓ Residual value after depreciation</p>

      <h3>Operating Lease (Rental)</h3>

      <p><strong>Deductions:</strong>
      <br>✓ Monthly rental payments (100% deductible)
      <br>✓ No depreciation (you don't own asset)
      <br>✓ No interest deduction (no loan)</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong>
      <br>✗ No ownership (asset builds less business value)
      <br>✗ Usage restrictions (often limited hours/year)
      <br>✗ No residual value (return asset at end)</p>

      <p><strong>Tax Advantage Comparison:</strong>
      <br>• Hire Purchase: Higher total deductions (capital allowance + interest)
      <br>• Lease: Consistent deductions but lower total
      <br><strong>Winner:</strong> Hire purchase offers better tax deductions for profitable businesses</p>

      <h2>0% Down Payment: Preserving Tax Deduction Capacity</h2>

      <h3>Traditional Financing (20% Down Payment)</h3>

      <p><strong>RM300,000 Prime Mover:</strong>
      <br>• Down payment: RM60,000
      <br>• Financed: RM240,000
      <br>• Capital allowance on: RM240,000 (not RM300,000)</p>

      <p><strong>Tax Impact:</strong>
      <br>• Year 1 deduction: RM96,000 (40% of RM240k)
      <br>• RM24,000 deduction lost (down payment portion)</p>

      <h3>0% Down Payment Financing</h3>

      <p><strong>Same RM300,000 Prime Mover:</strong>
      <br>• Down payment: RM0
      <br>• Financed: RM300,000
      <br>• Capital allowance on: RM300,000 (full amount)</p>

      <p><strong>Tax Impact:</strong>
      <br>• Year 1 deduction: RM120,000 (40% of RM300k)
      <br>• Maximum deduction preserved</p>

      <p><strong>Additional Benefit:</strong>
      <br>• RM60,000 preserved capital earns interest or generates revenue
      <br>• Can be invested in business operations (generates more deductible expenses)</p>

      <h2>Special Tax Incentives (2025)</h2>

      <h3>Automation Equipment Allowances (Check Current LHDN Guidelines)</h3>

      <p><strong>Industry 4.0 Automation:</strong>
      <br>• Additional accelerated allowances may apply
      <br>• MIDA (Malaysian Investment Development Authority) incentives
      <br>• Check specific equipment categories for special rates</p>

      <h3>Green Technology Incentives</h3>

      <p><strong>Electric Vehicles:</strong>
      <br>• Electric forklifts, electric lorries may qualify
      <br>• Income tax exemptions or rebates (check current schemes)
      <br>• Import duty exemptions (for electric vehicles)</p>

      <p><strong>Energy Efficient Equipment:</strong>
      <br>• Some energy-efficient equipment qualifies for special allowances
      <br>• Check current LHDN green technology incentives</p>

      <h2>Documentation: Proving Your Deductions</h2>

      <h3>Essential Records</h3>

      <p><strong>Invoices & Receipts:</strong>
      <br>• Equipment purchase invoice
      <br>• Financing agreement/loan schedule
      • Interest payment statements (show interest portion)
      <br>• Insurance payment receipts
      <br>• Maintenance and repair invoices</p>

      <p><strong>Asset Register:</strong>
      <br>• Maintain fixed asset register
      <br>• Track acquisition date, cost, depreciation schedule
      <br>• Disposal/sales documentation</p>

      <p><strong>LHDN Audit Risks:</strong>
      <br>• Ensure all deductions have supporting documents
      >• Keep records minimum 7 years (statutory requirement)
      <br>• Separate business and personal expenses clearly</p>

      <h2>Common Tax Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

      <h3>Mistake 1: Not Claiming All Deductions</h3>

      <p>Many businesses claim only equipment cost deduction but forget:
      <br>• Interest portion of installments (separate principal and interest)
      <br>• Insurance and road tax (fully deductible)
      <br>• Maintenance and repairs (even minor repairs add up)</p>

      <h3>Mistake 2: Mixing Business and Personal Use</h3>

      <p>Equipment used personally (e.g., director takes lorry home weekends):
      <br>• Portion of deduction disallowed (personal use ratio)
      <br>• Complex calculation required
      <br>• LHDN may audit and disallow portion of deductions</p>

      <h3>Mistake 3: Not Keeping Proper Records</h3>

      <p>LHDN requires evidence for every deduction claimed:
      <br>• Missing invoices = deduction disallowed
      <br>• Unsegregated expenses (personal + business) = complications
      <br>• Incomplete asset register = audit risks</p>

      <h3>Mistake 4: Wrong Depreciation Rates</h3>

      <p>Using incorrect allowance rates:
      <br>• Applying 20% to equipment qualifying for 40%
      <br>• Not claiming special allowances for eligible equipment
      <br>• Missing accelerated depreciation incentives</p>

